body: This PR adds functionality used in #4241

comment_data.body:
What is the meaning of the change?
This is the method cache, if you want to change the order, then the cached method. Not "cache method".

Both deal with exactly the same thing; one is the name, one is the pattern for catching that name. Therefore the two variable names should coincide, but whether `METHOD_CACHE_{NAME,PATTERN}` or `CACHE_METHOD_{NAME,PATTERN}` is not important IMO.

Ok, these names really cause confusion, I will change them to more descriptive ones.

.. probably for `_CACHE_NAME` and `_CACHE_NAME_PATTERN`
I think I'll change them as we come to some kind of agreement, there is no point in making a bunch of useless commits.
If we want to specify what kind of cache this is, then we can use "method cache" instead of "cache".

So what @h-vetinari?
You are ok with `_CACHE_NAME` and `_CACHE_NAME_PATTERN`
or is `_METHOD_CACHE_NAME` and `_METHOD_CACHE_NAME_PATTERN` better?

or something else?
I'm not calling any shots here, but I just wanted to note that the variables describing the same thing should be named consistently. Both your most recent suggestions sound OK to me from that POV.
